%p
  Direction Tour Marketing is part of an overwhelmingly visual industry, and
  they needed to update their old website to better fit into this highly visual
  world. When I got the call, I could have simply re-skinned their old site,
  but that&rsquo;s not how I like to work. I took the opportunity to sit down
  with their team to look at how they did their work, and then identified
  ways that the new website could make their job easier. The new Direction site
  isn&rsquo;t just a great looking brochure website; it&rsquo;s a tool that they
  use in their daily business.

.text--centered
  %figure.figure--mockup.figure--browser
    = lazy_image_tag "/assets/images/work/direction-browser.jpg", 1750, 949, "Direction Website on a wide screen"
  %figure.figure--mockup.figure--tablet
    = lazy_image_tag "/assets/images/work/direction-tablet.jpg", 800, 901, "Direction Website on a tablet"
  %figure.figure--mockup.figure--phone
    = lazy_image_tag "/assets/images/work/direction-phone.jpg", 600, 921, "Direction Website on a phone"

%p
  Direction&rsquo;s old site was a bear to manage, so we started by setting up a
  Content Management System that would encourage, rather than discourage,
  regular updating of site content. Then we added a client section to allow them
  to create and securely deliver client wrap reports through the site for all
  the projects they are working on. This not only allows them to deliver their
  reports faster, but also saves them the printing and postage costs that were
  required by their old reporting system. We also created a staff section to
  allow them to more easily search and manage their business directory,
  upgrading it from an old (and slow) Excel file.


%figure.figure--border
  = lazy_image_tag "/assets/images/work/direction-detail.jpg", 1000, 450, "Detail view of a case study page"
